sentences: Antonio Guillermo "Tony" Succar (born 18 May 1986), is a Peruvian-American percussionist, composer, arranger, bandleader, and producer.
When he was two years old his family emigrated to the United States and settled in Miami, Florida.
Since he was 3 years old Tony started playing the Peruvian cajón.
Succar attended Miami Sunset Senior High School in Miami-Dade County.
At the time his ambition was to be a professional soccer player, and he played in several teams, including his high school team when it won the 2004 state championships.
Succar gained a Bachelor of Arts in Jazz Performance in 2008 and went on to study for a master's degree, which he gained in 2010.
Succar gained a Bachelor of Arts in Jazz Performance in 2008 and went on to study for a master's degree, which he gained in 2010.
On 21 September 2010, Succar released an album recorded at his graduate recital, a live concert featuring Mixtura at Miami's Wertheim Performing Arts Center.
After graduating from FIU, Succar became an artist-in-residence there in 2012, continuing to work with the school's music students on a number of projects.
In 2019, Succar was nominated for a Latin Grammy Award in four separate categories, winning for Best Salsa Album and as Producer of the Year.
